        <name>6.2.1.3 Hyperbolic functions</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;h4&gt;The odd and even parts of the exponential function&lt;/h4&gt;&lt;p&gt;Using the approach outlined above we see that the even part of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(e^x\)&lt;/span&gt; is &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\dfrac{1}{2}(e^x+e^{-x})\)&lt;/span&gt; and the odd part of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(e^x\)&lt;/span&gt; is &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\dfrac{1}{2}(e^x-e^{-x})\)&lt;/span&gt; We give these new functions special names: &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh x\)&lt;/span&gt; (pronounced &#8216;cosh&#8217; &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x\)&lt;/span&gt;) and &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\sinh x\)&lt;/span&gt; (pronounced &#8216;shine&#8217; &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x\)&lt;/span&gt;).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="HELM_keypoint"&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Key Point: Hyperbolic functions&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[\cosh x \equiv \dfrac{1}{2}(e^x+e^{-x})\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[\sinh x \equiv \dfrac{1}{2}(e^x-e^{-x})\]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;
These two functions, when added and subtracted, give &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\[\begin{align*} \cosh x+\sinh x &amp;amp;\equiv e^x, \\ \cosh x-\sinh
x &amp;amp;\equiv e^{-x}.\end{align*}\]&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;The graphs of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh x\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\sinh x\)&lt;/span&gt; are shown in the below figure.&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/6-2-fig-1-sinhcoshgraph.svg" alt="" width="380" height="257" role="presentation" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Figure&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\sinh x\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh x\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Note that &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh x&amp;gt;0\)&lt;/span&gt; for all values of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x\)&lt;/span&gt; and that &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\sinh x\)&lt;/span&gt; is zero only when &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x=0\)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
